---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { site } from "../data/site";

const slug = "/do-colleges-look-at-weighted-or-unweighted-gpa";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "Do colleges look at weighted or unweighted GPA?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Colleges consider both weighted and unweighted GPA. Unweighted GPA shows your core academic performance, while weighted GPA reflects course difficulty such as honors or AP classes."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "Which GPA matters more for college admissions?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Unweighted GPA provides a consistent baseline across schools, but weighted GPA helps colleges evaluate how challenging your coursework was."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "Do colleges recalculate GPA?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Many colleges recalculate GPA using their own system to fairly compare students from different schools with different grading scales."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<GuideLayout
  title="Do Colleges Look at Weighted or Unweighted GPA?"
  description="Learn whether colleges use weighted or unweighted GPA, how admissions teams evaluate your grades, and what matters most for acceptance."
  slug={slug}
  heroTitle="Do Colleges Look at Weighted or Unweighted GPA?"
  heroText="If you're applying to college, you may be wondering whether weighted or unweighted GPA matters more. The answer is that colleges look at both — but they use them in different ways."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Answer</h2>
  <p>
    Colleges look at <strong>both weighted and unweighted GPA</strong>.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unweighted GPA</strong> shows your academic performance on a standard 4.0 scale</li>
    <li><strong>Weighted GPA</strong> reflects course difficulty (AP, honors, dual enrollment)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Most colleges use both to understand <strong>how well you performed</strong> and
    <strong>how challenging your classes were</strong>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Colleges Look at Both</h2>
  <p>
    Schools across the country use different grading systems. Some weight GPAs heavily,
    while others do not weight them at all.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because of this, colleges often:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Use <strong>unweighted GPA</strong> for consistency across applicants</li>
    <li>Use <strong>weighted GPA</strong> to evaluate course rigor</li>
    <li>Review your <strong>transcript</strong> to see the actual classes you took</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In many cases, colleges will also <strong>recalculate your GPA</strong> using their own system.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Which GPA Matters More?</h2>
  <p>
    Neither one is more important on its own.
  </p>

  <p>
    Instead, admissions officers look at:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your GPA</li>
    <li>The difficulty of your classes</li>
    <li>Your overall academic trend</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For example:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>A 3.8 unweighted GPA with AP classes is very strong</li>
    <li>A 4.5 weighted GPA shows you challenged yourself</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The combination of <strong>performance + rigor</strong> is what matters most.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Do Colleges Recalculate GPA?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes, many colleges recalculate GPA to create a fair comparison between students.
  </p>

  <p>
    They may:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Remove weighting</li>
    <li>Focus on core academic classes</li>
    <li>Standardize grades onto a 4.0 scale</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This means your reported GPA is important, but your <strong>actual grades and classes matter more</strong>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Calculate Your GPA</h2>
  <p>
    If you want to understand your GPA better, try using a calculator:
  </p>

  <p>
    👉 <a href="/gpa-calculator">GPA Calculator</a>
  </p>

  <p>
    You can calculate both weighted and unweighted GPA and see how your classes affect your results.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>
  <p>
    Colleges do not choose between weighted and unweighted GPA — they use both.
  </p>

  <p>
    What matters most is:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Strong grades</li>
    <li>Challenging courses</li>
    <li>Consistent performance</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Focus on doing well in your classes and taking opportunities to challenge yourself.
  </p>
</section>

</GuideLayout>